{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487388"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:08:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:08:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"337"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/337"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.05,0.14,0.1,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"337"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57902"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/337"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"337"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43361"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"207"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2453"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2460"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2502"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11015"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17082"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57902"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman present to the Emergency Department with perforated diverticular disease and localised peritonitis. She undergoes an emergency laparotomy and a Hartmann procedure (sigmoid colectomy, end-colostomy, and mucus fistula) is performed. She makes good progress for the first two days and then on the third evening becomes confused, disoriented, and noisy. She is tremulous and observed to be scratching her skin. On examination she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 109/min, blood pressure 165/98 mmHg and temperature 38.3\u00b0C. Her laboratory investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 110 g/L (125 \u2013 160)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELeukocytes 11.6 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0 \u2013 11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean corpuscular volume 105 fl (80 \u2013 96)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 145x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (150 - 450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlbumin 30 g/L (36 - 46)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBilirubin 18 \u03bcmol/L (2 - 24)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDirect bilirubin 7 \u03bcmol/L (\u0026lt;5.1)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAspartate aminotransferase 253 U/L (\u0026lt;45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlanine aminotransferase 122 U/L (\u0026lt;55)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlkaline phosphatase 102 U/L (30 - 110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGamma-glutamyl transferase 242 U/L (\u0026lt;60)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this problem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alcohol withdrawal","Chest infection","Postoperative delirium","Opiate toxicity","Postoperative cognitive dysfunction"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhilst many causes of confusion need to be considered in the postoperative setting, the tremulousness and tactile hallucinations along with fever, tachycardia, and hypertension raise suspicion for delirium tremens (DT) which typically occurs about three days after alcohol was last consumed in the setting of \u003Cstrong\u003Ealcohol withdrawal\u003C/strong\u003E. This patient\u0027s alcohol use is suggested by her typical lab findings (eg, macrocytic anaemia, AST:ALT ratio of 2:1). DT is characterised by confusion, disorientation, diaphoresis, fever, tachycardia, and hypertension. Patients may also experience hallucinations, most commonly tactile hallucinations of bugs crawling under their skin (formication). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlcohol withdrawal can present differently depending on the days since the last alcoholic drink was consumed. Within the first 24 hours, patients may present with mild withdrawal symptoms (eg, anxiety, tremors, diaphoresis, palpitations). Patients with alcohol withdrawal may also present with generalised tonic-clonic seizures within the first two days after sudden cessation of alcohol. Alcoholic hallucinosis presents with visual, auditory, or tactile hallucinations within the first two days since the last drink. The differentiation between alcoholic hallucinosis and DT can be made based on vital signs. Vital signs are stable in alcoholic hallucinosis while patients with DT usually have fever, tachycardia, and hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest infection\u003C/strong\u003E may have a similar presentation. However, chest infection may lead to sepsis resulting in hypotension, in contrast to this patient\u0027s hypertension. This patient\u0027s slightly elevated leukocyte count can be seen in post-op patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpiate toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E leads to respiratory depression and overall CNS depression. This patient\u0027s agitative state is suggestive of either a withdrawal from a CNS-depressing substance or toxicity from a CNS-activating substance. In a hospital setting, it is much more likely that this patient is suffering from an alcohol withdrawal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPostoperative delirium (POD) \u003C/strong\u003Ecan occur within minutes and up to seven days in hospital, or until discharge. It is commonly recognised in the post-anaesthesia care unit. POD can present as a disorder in thought processes and can affect memory, comprehension and attention. Subtypes of POD include hyperactive, hypoactive and mixed-operative delirium. Although this is a potential complication, alcohol withdrawal is a more specific and likely cause in this clinical scenario, as previously explained.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPostoperative cognitive dysfunction (POCD) \u003C/strong\u003Etimeframe onset remains to be defined but can be detectable seven days after surgery. POCD is defined as a cognitive decline from a patient\u0027s baseline in one or multiple domains. For example: difficulty in writing, financial management, and memory, which can have tangible effects once patients are discharged home. Given that the patient\u0027s symptom presentation occurred within seven days, it is unlikely that POCD is the most appropriate diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alcohol withdrawal may present in hospitalised patients with chronic alcoholism due to the inability to access alcohol. It is usually characterised by symptoms ranging from mild withdrawal (eg, tremors, diaphoresis, anxiety) to seizures, visual hallucinations, and delirium tremens."],"references":["Marcantonio ER. Delirium in Hospitalized Older Adults. N Engl J Med 2017;377:1456-66. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMcp1605501","Robinson TN, Eiseman B. Postoperative delirium in the elderly: diagnosis and management. Clin Interv Aging. 2008;3(2):351-5. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2546478/","Brodier EA, Cibelli M. Postoperative cognitive dysfunction in clinical practice. BJA Educ. 2021;21(2):75-82. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7810820/#:~:text=Postoperative%20cognitive%20dysfunction%20describes%20a,elderly%20patients%20after%201%20yr.\u0026text=Cognitive%20decline%20may%20be%20noted,multiple%20of%20the%20cognitive%20domains."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43361"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"337"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43361"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-27T23:01:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-27T23:02:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"337"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57902"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suit